segments.text: There's always that.
In any organization, you have that problem.
But anyway, you wanted to go back to the origination of what the conference was.
How about your getting up to Texas A&M, if you don't mind?
How did that happen?
Well, I'll tell you how it happened.
My mother wanted me to become a doctor.
So my mother died early.
But anyway, I had planned on going to Rice.
So I was there.
Accepted at Rice.
But that summer, I went over to Louisiana to work in oil fields.
Where did you work in Louisiana?
I worked in Vinton, Louisiana, in some little wells my brother had, Johnny had.
And then I decided I wanted to become a program engineering geologist.
So then I changed.
Instead of going to Rice, I registered at A&M.
and started to take a program in engineering and geology.
And that's how I came to A&M.
Had the brother been there or anyone in the family at all?
Johnny was a graduate of A&M and so was my older brother.
He had gone for a year and then went over to Texas.
And Johnny was a chemical engineer graduate of A&M.
He was about seven years my senior.
He worked for Exxon.
Then he was out busy drilling a few little wells, working over wells.
He left Exxon by the time I was a senior in high school.
And that summer before school started, the university started, and I went there.
I'd gone back to...

to my school at Galveston, even after I graduated a year because I was too young, too small, and I had to take a third year of Latin to be able to qualify for taking pre-med or whatever to go to Rice.
So I went back.
But I was now taking also trigonometry and solid geometry.
So I did so well in those, I decided I'd be an engineer and geologist when I decided to get into oil and gas.
Brother did straight geology.
Did you ride the train up to College Station, or how did you go?

Yeah, I rode the train when I went to College Station, and I may have heard it because when I talked to the, I think to one of the graduation things at A&M, I'd mentioned that when I got off the train, because my aunt put me on the train in Houston.
She drove up from Galveston, put me on the train.
I drove up, and I had to get off all alone, 16-year-old kid,
Walking across the campus, wondering what the hell was going to happen.
It was a long walk, huh?
A long walk.
Up that hill.
You know, from the old train station over to campus there.
But it was a very nostalgic memory.
But anyway, A&M was a great school.
And, you know, for $450 a year, I could go to school in a room and board and everything.
And it was tough.
And my father didn't have any money.
I'd have to do some work in the mess hall.
And I built bookshelves.
And I was cleaning and pressing laundry.
And I had a candy concession where the damn football players would steal all the time and not pay me.
And then I did, it was tough the first couple of years, but I managed to get by.
And the last year, I made money.
I made more money when I graduated than I got from Amical when I went to work for them.
I developed, I was the one who originated the stationery that had its beautiful gold and embossed field artillery and signal corps.
I originated that.
In fact, there's some sheets of that in the archives.
It used to be just plain print, maroon print on the white paper.
So I got a San Antonio printer.
who developed that for me, and then I had an agent in every dormitory.
And I was making $300 a month when I got it from school, and I only took a $126 salary at A&M University.
I mean, at Amical University, Amical, in South Louisiana.
So I took a cut in salary to leave A&M.
But that, I wanted to take engineering, and I didn't want to go in the Army.
I knew the war was coming on.
We all knew that, but I wanted to get some experience.
So what I decided, even though I was offered a full commission because...
I had excellent grades, and I was in battalion command and everything at A&M, but I didn't want to get in the service.
The war hadn't come on.
But I was a reserve officer, and then when I was in South Louisiana, I think it was September before the war, they called me to active duty.
I went with the Corps of Engineers, and I did all construction on Dixon Gun Plant, Sergeant Ernest Depot, all these airfields around Texas here.
with the Corps of Engineers.
So I got tremendous experience.
I ended up first lieutenant, supervising 150 people.
And you were mainly involved in construction.
Mainly engineering and construction.
Engineering officer, what I was, assistant engineering officer.
And therefore, I got great experience.
And then when the war ended, I lost four and a half years.
So I just came to Houston and decided, to hell with it.
I lost all my contemporaries that stayed with the company for some reason or other because of
being classified as 4F.
They had come up, and they ranked pretty well in the company.
And the company offered me a job, because they thought I was a good engineering geologist.
And I had been involved in South Louisiana, which was a tremendous field for Amaco.
It was called Stanley in the old days, Stanley Oil and Gas.
And they had a tremendous operation there.
And I had a lot of experience in the year and a half that I was down.
So therefore, I came to Houston and said, this is where I want to set up and become a consultant.
Were you in production, primarily, or exploration?
I was in exploration, geology, and production.
They had exploitation engineers, you see.
And we did all the exploitation.
And we didn't do the basic regional geology.
We did the exploitation geology and engineering, too.
So I did both, because my background was both.
And therefore, when I came to Houston,
My brother had come here also, and he had some friends.
And I was able to get six people to fund me $50 each with a little override to see if I could find oil and gas for them.
And that was it.
And I would do the deals.
I'd do the geology and engineering, and then I'd get my brother and my partner.
That's all we had, one girl in the office with us.
They'd go down to Esperson Drugstore and sell the deals.
Were you doing any seismograph work, or how were you doing?
No, I would do subsurface geology.
In fact, when it first started, we had so little money.
None of you may have heard this before.
I had a friend called John Todd who had a Cambie blueprint, and I couldn't afford to buy the logs.
So I'd borrow the logs at 6 o'clock.
I'd work about 3 in the morning, and I'd bring them back for 8 o'clock.
He wouldn't charge me.
And I'd do some of my geology to start with, you see.
So that's the way.
And then we would get people at Bacchus for 32nd overriding interest.
Eventually, we'd get more.
And eventually, we'd get a quarter in that front.
We'd get big people like Bob Smith.
And we had all the Jewish people in town taking deals for us called the Big Nine.
Oh, they were good, too.
Wine Gardens, all the Jewish people that you know, the Battlesteins, they're all to Oshkosh.
And you were working this area primarily?
We were working the Gulf Coast region here.
Except that we did work some areas, just like our North Texas prospect came to us
from a Chicago bookie, believe it or not, through one of my partners.
That's a hell of a story in itself.
But he asked me to check, and I said, hell, what the hell does a Chicago bookie know about Texas Auto and Gas?
He just had a deal, and I found out it came to him through one of my friends been trying to sell it, named Allison Miles.
I didn't know him, but he had gone to A&M.
Had been trying for two years to sell the deal.
He couldn't sell it to the Chicago bookie.
He wanted to know if we'd look at it.
One of my participants called him, General Pulaski.
He wasn't a general, but they called him that.
He said, come on, you've got to look at this deal.
I said, well, all right, General, I'll look at it.
And that's where we made one of the big discoveries on the Texas.
So you never know.
No, you don't.
But anyway.
Did you ever read that book about Petillo Higgins?
No, I haven't seen that book there.
I haven't read that one.
It's quite a story.
Did you ever know him?
No, I know of him, but I don't know him.
Do you have the book?
David Norton was going to give it to you.
I think I have the book.
I think you really enjoyed that.
Higgins did a great job on Spinal Tap.
There's no question.
Quite an adventurer.
Well, oil and gas are that way.
A lot of these people are that way.
But the oil and gas was good.
We began slowly, and we kept getting a little better and better interest in it.
We found a lot of oil and gas.
I did consulting work for Glenn McCarthy and a lot of other people.
Eddie Scurll, I'm glad, the old-timers you've heard of.
Floyd Carsten and them, besides creating our own company.
I was doing both things.
The consulting work, I'd do, and I'd sell deals to them, make a little override there.
But we began to build our company.
That's where we really started our company.
So most of the oil and gas we had, we found most of it ourselves.
So that's the difference where we're at than most companies.
When did you organize?
What was your first company organized as, or when did you do that?
It was organized in 1946.
That's when I came in January of 46.
It was organized probably in June of 46.
So you organized right away.
You and I just consulted.
It was organized as Rock Soil.
And Rob's got some history on that.
He's got some history on that.
In 46, and they had three partners, and one guy named Jimmy Gray, after he was in about six months, I was getting a little overhyped for doing the work for them.
He said, I got a third interest.
I'm going to Oklahoma.
I'm leaving.
Do you want to buy it?
So I got the gentleman to back my note for $9,000.
And he had a little money in, so I bought him out for the third of this little fledgling company that just started.
I think we had one well at Kaplan and one well at North Kiran.
So I bought my interest in it, and the general helped me bank it.
He signed my note for me.
So General Pulaski.
But that's how I got in the company.
Then, of course, we started building the company.
In the meantime, I was also doing consulting work for a number of people around here that would pay me enough, because I had two kids here and one on the way.
In other words, it's very, and I get that a little naive, to think that with a year and a half experience, I could become a consulting engineer and geologist.
And that's what I did.
That's what you really did, yeah.
But I knew Houston was the place to be, so that's one thing I picked the right place to be.
That's when things were taking over.
There was a backlog of prospects that couldn't drill wells during the war because steel was unavailable.
We were furnishing all our allies with all the oil that they had.
And therefore, I knew that Houston was the place to be.
Then when did you organize Mitchell Energy Development?
Well, after the oil, rock soil, then we created a company called
I think it's Christie, Mitchell, and Mitchell, which is a successor to Rock Soil.
And that was the three partners, myself and my brother Johnny.
They were older than I was.
And myself.
They would outsell the deals I'd do with the children in engineering.
And we finally hired a couple of people to help us because we taught drilling wells, making a few wells.
And I would say we organized that probably in the early 50 or 51, Christie, Mitchell, and Mitchell.
And then we started making a lot of discoveries with Palacios and North Texas in 53.
And we've discovered a lot of oil and gas reservoirs and fields.
And then we changed it to George Mitchell Associates.
And then in 72, we became Mitchell Engine Development when we went public.
That's when I first met Joe.
And when I went to Chicago to make presentations to, he's working with Hershey, Rodman, and Druck.
to see if they thought that we could sell our product to the investment community.
You know, whether they thought we had enough, whatever it was.
And they thought, you know, they helped us get the information around the country.
So that when we went public, the stock sold when it was sold.
Oh, probably a third of the company, that's all that was sold down, more than that.
And my brother, I had bought out most of his, and then I bought out my other partner before that.
My brother had about 20% of the company I had.
more than that.
And he eventually sold most of his and did other things.
So then I ended up with most of the company, probably 63%.
What was your first experience in real estate?
Well, the first experience was very interesting.
First experience was, I guess, back in 1961 or two.
Someone, a person in Galveston I knew named Spro, a woman,
called me and said, I knew him in high school, George, that my husband who just died left some real estate to the Texas bank.
We used to be in a Texas bank down here where the Chronicle building was.
Some husband, wasn't it?
Society for the Prevention of Frailty of Animals, yeah.
She could get the income, but then the property would go to the dogs, so to speak.
She said, they're getting ready to sell these people, and they really got a rip-off going on.
And they got a piece out of the memorial where those apartments are right there, and then they had a piece...
which is now an industrial park of the Woodlands.
That was before we even conceded the Woodlands.
Now, what year is this, roughly?
That was about 61 or 62.
And so I found out that the district judge in Conroe had some sort, or at least where the trust head department had to go, had a deal going on.
So I threatened the bank with a lawsuit for her benefit, and that if I got it, I'd get a quarter of their profits.
And therefore, this land was split up.
The judge worked out a deal.
that he would take part of Deer Conroe and let us have 500 acres on the edge of the well before he even didn't think it'd be part of the woods.
Had nothing to do with the woods.
For $49 an acre.
And it had about a $50 acre of timber on it.
So we were able to buy it that way.
Now that is the first piece of real estate we had taken on.
We had done some
doing with some housing development with a person named Norman Dobbins back in 63, 64, doing a little housing development in several spots around the country, which we didn't make money.
We lost money on that.
This was strictly as an investment thing?
Well, we were participating with him trying to help make it work.
He was pretty good at design and creativity, but he was a very poor businessman.
So we had to
And we lost money on that, and we finally had to buy him out.
But that wasn't very much money.
We were just playing with it.
We didn't do it.
But about 62, 63, 64, then we had bought Pelican Island about in 62 or 63.
We worked with A&M to take the A&M campus.
We had looked at it.
But then I got in real estate that way because we were using leverage and all of that.
Pelican Island, I had a deal made buying it from,
Mary Chapman Scott, they had about $10 million spent in it.
And they had a big lawsuit with the city.
I was able to solve the lawsuit, so I bought it for $1.8 million.
But I had a deal with Shell to sell 50 acres for about $1.6 million.
So then I closed the deal.
I sold it.
And I had $200,000 or $300,000 left in Pelican Island.
Then I promised to give A&M the acres they had, the 100 acres they had for the institute there.
So then, of course, what got me into really the woodlands
It was about that time, in 64, we'd have more oil.
And this is all you had done, though, in terms of land and development?
We knew in 62 that energy was in trouble.
I knew in 62 that that's when they opened the floodgates and all the Persian Gulf oil, Kuwait and Iran, and they were driving us up a wall and importing oil.
And the price of oil was down to a quarter barrel.
And I could foresee, and that Laubel Railroad Commission of Texas was only eight days for every oil well.
So we concentrated on gas because we knew gas was going to be the future.
So I concentrated all our effort on gas.

And knowing that unless we did something else, we would probably be out of business because we could see oil was going to be in deep trouble as long as it continued flooding this country with cheap oil.
But you were discovering, but you weren't trying to produce the gas.
We were discovering.
We were producing.
Oh, yeah, we produced every foot we could get at $0.03 a thousand.
The first gas contract I made was $0.03 a thousand at North Huron.
And then it finally got up to six or eight cents.
That was a pretty good price then.
But we knew that gas was undervalued and we could make deals with major companies to drill gas properties easier than you could for oil properties.
So I thought gas was the future from the standpoint of energy demand.
And we concentrated 80% of everything related to gas.
So we knew that.
So then I started working on some of our,

brokers they're out with all these brokers working for us you know 10 or 15 people they make it if they make a deal they make a dollar they don't make a deal with no money so they're starving to death so i said well if you find a piece of real estate up here you know where we can steal you know we'll may try to figure out how to leverage ourselves and buy it so when i had this piece of land that i bought from the judge and the bank here that i end up with that three or four acres out there i had this um person that um
Max Newland, who was a forester up in that area, to cut the timber so we could get some money.

So he cut the timber on that land, and I said, well, Max, if you know of a deal that we could put together, leverage-wise, and make a real good deal, because we don't have any money, we have to use leverage, see what you can put together.
So he came in one day and he said, I'll tell you what, there's a 50,000-acre block up here called the Grogan, Cork, and Lumber Company.
So that may be possible.
And David Bentley, everybody had been trying to buy it for five years.
And the problem was they had three family groups.
They were down to cousins.
The brothers had died off.
They had a big lumber mill that had burned down, and they rebuilt it the same old-fashioned way, which was not efficient.
They were in trouble.
They had 80 heirs, some of them worth several hundred thousand dollars, couldn't afford a pack of cigarettes.
And therefore, I said, all right, let me see if I can't put this together.
So it took me two years and 62 or so to buy the Grogan-Cocker-Lummet coming.
I had to settle those three lawsuits.
I'm in three family groups fighting.
And I bought it for $125.25 an acre, 50,000 acres, of which only 4,000 were woodlands, and the rest were scattered in the county.
And the reason that the way I figured the price, that I could sell the timber to Louisiana Pacific, and I had some minerals,
So I figured the only thing I could afford to pay would be $125 an acre, or about $6 million for 50,000 acres, because I could pay the interest on the Louisiana timber contract and the minerals.
And I got the Bank of Southwest at that time.
Harold Vance used to be my professor at A&M, thought a lot of me.
And he was able to say, okay, I'll make you a loan if you can get a release on the land, 20% release on the land, 15% payment.
So I got the Grover and Cochran heirs to give me a release.
Joe, you've probably never heard this story.
I've never heard of it.
Release of the land for paying 15%.
And the bank gave me the money because I didn't have the money.

So then I took the residual of the 50,000 acres and went to Great Southern about six months later and made a full $6 million 20-year loan, just paid interest for 20 years so I could pay it off on timber.
Well, that was a land deal.
It had nothing to do with the woodlands.
Now, who was Doolin with?

the guy who originally me and me and me myself and this max newland who i then hired him to be my forester you see and you ought to put his name down he can tell you all right then then right after that i found out about the foster lumber company which is what kingwood is so i made a run at that 50 000 more acres even though we're drilling oil and gas wells over here
for difficult times, and I had to use leverage, you see.
So I made a run at them, and I was able to get 21% locked up for a dollar a share.
There were a bunch of heirs, and they were in Kansas City, Missouri.
I was after the company, another 50,000 acres for myself.
And I had a deal made with the 21% at 125 an acre, 150 an acre on that one.
And then I got Boise Cascade,
to come in for half interest if they would put up the $750,000 I needed to buy up to 51% and then dissolve the company.
But they wouldn't put it up unless I had an option on the 51%.
And the guys at 51% wouldn't do it unless I had the money.
So I couldn't quite do that.
And so what happened while I was negotiating with it, Exxon and King Ranch moved in and paid them $300 an acre.
That's where Kingwood is.
But it was a bad piece of land.
I was going to red flag it, you know, just sell it off for 10 acres, 20 francs.
So that went away.
But we made, the company made, because then I had 125 an acre and 115 an acre, and I sold it for two or three to Exxon.
So we made a million dollars.
I was really the first green male around here.
Now, when was the Foster, when we do... That was about 62, 63, right after both the group and Cochran.
Yeah, okay.
Now, there's no concept of the Woodlands or anything.
We've been piddling with a little, a couple of these little subdivisions around with Norman Dobbins called Pace Center Home, but nothing of any magnitude.
Let me pause just one second now.
Meanwhile, while you're doing all of this, there is a lot of activity going on down south around NASA and so forth.
Are you paying any attention to that or thinking about it?
Only that what happened at Exxon made a deal
to let them have that acreage down there, Frenswood did, to the 5,000, whatever it is, through Lyndon Johnson, to do the space thing.
I didn't think that had too much relation, except it meant that Houston had another anchor besides just oil and gas.
But that was very embryonic at that time.
Even when the Woodlands first started, it was just beginning.
But they were able to start Clear Lake.
They'd already started Clear Lake before then.
Frenswood had it.
But then when NASA came in, it really made Clear Lake a lot better.
They bought Clear Lake.
They didn't want the Clear Lake.
They bought it because of the oil field Exxon did, and the West made them take the damn land at $100 an acre.
They didn't want the land, the 20,000 acres.
Well, they took it, and then they finally decided to do Clear Lake because it was near the bay.

And then after a while, when they found out that there was going to be a NASA, they worked on President Johnson to get them to take whatever acres that NASA got out of it as part of the deal to make Clear Lake go, you see.
And all the universities worked with them.
But we knew about it, and we knew it would help Houston, but we thought it would have nothing to do with it.
So then we missed the Foster Lumber Company deal.
But we had the $50,000, I guess.
So I then started.
I had Carl Kamrath start in 66.
What happened in the early 60s, 64, 65, we began to have these terrible riots.
The Vietnam War was on.
Bedford-Stuyvesant was having a riot up in New York City.
Watts was having a riot.
And I went to several of these YPO meetings to understand the plight of our cities.
They're all in desperate shape.
And what was happening in my reckoning, that what was destroying our cities was the proliferation of political subdivisions around the central core, and they can't manage it.
And that there ought to be a better way to evolve an area.
But why did you get in?
That's sort of unusual.
Here you are.
Because the organization I belong to called Young Presidents Organization.
Called what?
Young Presidents Organization.
Whenever we went anywhere, we didn't talk about business all the time.
We talked about philosophy and humanities.
And we exposed ourselves to the thoughts of really what makes a nation work.
And these are local CEOs?
Well, it's a national organization.
It's a national organization.
We have about 30 members here.
And then, you see, at that time, our company was over worth more than a couple million dollars.
So if you had over 50 people or 100 people, you could qualify to be a young president before you're 40.
You had to have a presidency before you're 40 years old or you don't qualify.
So there were a lot of entrepreneurs.
There were a lot of them that just inherited money, and they're usually duds, mad because they don't know what they did themselves or what their father did for them.
So this was a hell of an organization.
It really was.
So therefore, I was exposed to really wanting what was destroying our cities.
And then I got to thinking, well, why can't we do it better?
And what other place would be better to do it than Houston?
Because Houston was going to go to 5 million people.
I knew that.
I knew they were the beauty, because I lived in Memorial by that time.
I finished my house.
I lived in Memorial from 58 on.
When you came from service into Houston, you moved into Houston.
You didn't stay in the office.
Oh, no, I moved into Houston.
I had an apartment my aunt had because there were no apartments available, and I ran that apartment house.
Cynthia and I will never do it again.
We had to scrape these plaster walls and paint the damn thing.
I said, never again will I do that.
She agreed with me, but then it was tough, and we had two kids and one other wife.
So it was tough.
It was tough for her.
But then I was able to have a place to live here because my aunt was here.
And then the...
We first moved in with her mother, then I got the apartment, because I managed the apartment on Elgin, on Fannin and Elgin, that my aunt owned.
So I was able to manage the apartment, because there was no housing available for a while.
The first move was sent to his mother for about a month and a half, until I got the apartment, then we moved there, and then we had to redo it ourselves.
But later on, I bought a house, so I started getting some royalties, so I ended up building a house.
I had Ford, Powell & Carson design it from San Antonio,
on North McGregor.
Beautiful area.
Ford, who did it?
Ford?
Ford Powell and Carson out of San Antonio.
Neil Ford designed my house.
Because I knew one of the architects that I was in the Army with, and he worked for Neil Ford at that time.
Who was that?
He was named Jerry Rogers.
Okay.
So Neil Ford designed my first house.
It was only a six-down, beautiful house.
Right on Timbercrest on North McGregor in a beautiful wooded area.
But what happened, when the Supreme Court ruling came in, I knew it was going to go all black.
So then I moved to Memorial into the Spring Branch School District, because I just wanted to go ahead.
I guess we had seven, eight kids at that time, and we just wanted to be sure we got a good decent education here.
So that's why I moved out to Memorial area.
And then we built a house in 65, which we finished in 65, a big house up there.
So anyway, by that time, I had gone around the country.
It seemed I was destroying the nation, in my opinion.
And how do you do it better?
So this is what we got thinking.
I asked Carl Cameron, I said, all right, Carl, and you pick, but you'll see their names in the book.
How many acres would I need to build a town of 100,000?
So they made that sketch.
And that sketch is fairly accurate of what we did.
So we moved before Pierre and Carl came out and they said, you need 20,000 acres.
We only had 4,000 in that spot there.
But see, I didn't think that was the right spot.
looked at the 1960 I-45 area, right where the corner was.
I actually optioned 2,500 acres at $2,500, which I still have it now.
But then I couldn't get the 10,000 to 15,000 acres I need on the option, so I gave up on that sign.
That was about in 67, 65, right after Carl finished his math.
Then I said, well, the best place is, and we looked at where the airport was going to be.
We knew where the freeway in the airport was going to be.
I-45, and we knew where the airport was going to be.
We looked at the sonic problem, because if you get too close to the airport, you destroy the chance.
We looked at the freeway.
We looked at the beauty of the woods.
I had lived in Memorial.
I knew the Memorial.

In fact, one thing we found out by having this little pace at a home thing, that if we had a lot on the west side of town, and you had one with three trees and one with no trees, the one with three trees would get you $500 more.
So we knew the value of the forest, the beauty.
That's why Memorial is so popular.
In 1960, it was a hot thing at that time, but it's been screwed up by a bunch of small tracks.
It's a big mess.
It's like West Ham all over again.
So we didn't want to do that.
If you don't really design it properly, I didn't want to do it.
So then we turned around and said, okay.
Carl Cameron did his study.
Then I started with Carl Charlie Lively to start building the block.
It took 300 transactions.
to build a block.
And you're trying to, you're going for 20,000 acres, or you're... Charles Lavery, I guess, you got all the data from him in the first quarter.
Yeah.
So then I had to build a block for 20,000 acres.
And it was very difficult going with the Catholic Church and with the Celan Smith Foundation and with this fellow McCann at Waco Bank in Woodsville.
Gee, what a terrible negotiation.
Well, anyway, starting about in 1969,
We heard about the University of Houston.
We were building the block.
We wanted to build a north campus and a south campus.
So we went there, and they took them out before we'd ever done anything.
And they agreed that they would like to have a site in the woodlands for the north campus.
That was 68, 69.
We've got some history about that in there.
And then we retained.
What I did then is I went out to Columbia.
First, I had sent people, well,
